The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Sept. 18 (PTI): India will launch a campaign in the US tomorrow to promote itself as a global tourist destination.           dia Calling, is a two-day programme, will be organised in Los Angeles by the tourism ministry in collaboration with National Geographic channel. The campaign will include road shows, photo exhibitions, a handicrafts festival and cultural shows.                   
	 Kanpur (PTI): A prisoner was mistakenly released from Kanpur jail after he impersonated another inmate. Jitendra Shukla, who was booked for possessing illegal weapons, was released on bail instead of his cellmate, Ankur.                   
	 Washington (PTI): Temples in the United States and Canada will have e-services to improve connectivity. During the fourth annual Hindu Mandir Executives Conference, executives representing 111 temples and Hindu organisations from more than 25 states of the US and Canada decided to develop a software.                  
	 Srinagar (PTI): India has issued a passport to separatist leader Syed Ali Shah Geelani to visit his ailing son in Pakistan. Geelani has got a passport for the first time since militancy broke out in Jammu and Kashmir. Sources said Omar Abdullah had intervened to ensure 79-year-old Geelani got the passport.                   
	 Chennai (PTI): A heart transplant has been performed in Chennai on a 25-year-old woman with the heart of a brain-dead teenager. The government hospital performed a five-hour surgery. The teenager, whose heart was donated, had had an accident.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Kolkata-Dhaka Maitree Express will remain suspended till September 23 for fear that heavy rush during Id may hamper customs and immigration formalities. Bangladesh railways had requested the suspension, an official said. The service will resume from September 26.                                                                                                                           
